k, England":"英国素福爾可梅特費爾德","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"英国英格兰坎布利其爾","lifeSummary":"Richard Bartholomew Everard III是Richard Mountbernard Everard Jr.的儿子，于1393年出生在英国坎布利其爾列福林頓。他于大约1416年与Agnes Fleet在英国英格兰坎布利其爾结婚。他们至少是3个儿子的父母。他去世于1423年在他的家乡享年30岁。"},"hr":{"1393–1423":"1393.–1423.","1395–Male":"1395–preminuo","1395–Female":"1395–preminula","1417–Male":"1417–preminuo","1419–Male":"1419.–preminuo","1365–Male":"1365–preminuo","Abt 1419":"oko 1419.","1423":"1423.","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","1393":"1393.","1419":"1419.","Abt 1417":"oko 1417.","Abt 1416":"oko 1416.","1417":"1417","Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, Engleska, United Kingdom","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, England","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1393–1423":"1393–1423","1395–Male":"1395–Zesnulý","1395–Female":"1395–Zesnulá","1417–Male":"1417–Zesnulý","1419–Male":"1419–Zesnulý","1365–Male":"1365–Zesnulý","Abt 1419":"okolo 1419","1423":"1423","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1419":"1419","Abt 1417":"okolo 1417","Abt 1416":"okolo 1416","1417":"1417","Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, Anglie","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, Anglie","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1393–1423":"1393–1423","1395–Male":"1395–Afdød","1395–Female":"1395–Afdød","1417–Male":"1417–Afdød","1419–Male":"1419–Afdød","1365–Male":"1365–Afdød","Abt 1419":"omkring 1419","1423":"1423","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1419":"1419","Abt 1417":"omkring 1417","Abt 1416":"omkring 1416","1417":"1417","Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, England","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1393–1423":"1393–1423","1395–Male":"1395–Overleden","1395–Female":"1395–Overleden","1417–Male":"1417–Overleden","1419–Male":"1419–Overleden","1365–Male":"1365–Overleden","Abt 1419":"circa 1419","1423":"1423","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1419":"1419","Abt 1417":"circa 1417","Abt 1416":"circa 1416","1417":"1417","Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, England","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1393–1423":"1393–1423","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","1395–Female":"1395–Deceased","1417–Male":"1417–Deceased","1419–Male":"1419–Deceased","1365–Male":"1365–Deceased","Abt 1419":"about 1419","1423":"1423","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1419":"1419","Abt 1417":"about 1417","Abt 1416":"about 1416","1417":"1417","Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, England","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Everard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Everett  .","French (northern), Walloon, and Dutch: variant of French and Walloon   Evrard  , Dutch   Everhard  .","Americanized form of German   Eberhardt   or   Everhardt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Everett","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English personal names <i>Everard</i> and <i>Everet</i>. These might occasionally be from the Old English form of the name, <i>Eoforheard</i> (from <i>eofor</i> ‘boar’ + <i>heard</i> ‘hardy, brave’), but many bearers of this name were undoubtedly Normans, who took it from the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Eburhard</i>, <i>Everhard</i>."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Bartholomew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of New Testament origin, the name of an apostle mentioned in all the synoptic gospels (Matthew, Mark, and Luke) and in the Acts of the Apostles. It is an Aramaic formation meaning ‘son of Talmai’, and has been assumed by many scholars to be a byname of the apostle   Nathaniel .  <i>Talmai</i> is a Hebrew name, said to mean ‘abounding in furrows’ (Numbers 13:22)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Bartholomew Everard III was born in 1393, in Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England as the son of Richard Mountbernard Everard Jr.. He married Agnes Fleet about 1416, in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1423, in his hometown, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1393–1423":"1393–1423","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1417–Male":"1417–Surnud","1419–Male":"1419–Surnud","1365–Male":"1365–Surnud","Abt 1419":"umbes 1419","1423":"1423","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1419":"1419","Abt 1417":"umbes 1417","Abt 1416":"umbes 1416","1417":"1417","Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, England","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1393–1423":"1393–1423","1395–Male":"1395–Kuollut","1395–Female":"1395–Kuollut","1417–Male":"1417–Kuollut","1419–Male":"1419–Kuollut","1365–Male":"1365–Kuollut","Abt 1419":"noin 1419","1423":"1423","1365":"1365","1395":"1395","1393":"1393","1419":"1419","Abt 1417":"noin 1417","Abt 1416":"noin 1416","1417":"1417","Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England","Of, Leverington, Cambridgeshire, England":"Leverington, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Metfield, Suffolk, England":"Metfield, Suffolk, England","Of, Wysbech, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1393–1423":"1393–1423","1395–Male":"